 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: automatic_top_up, balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer, beneficiary_not_allowed, cancel_transfer, card_payment_fee_charged, card_payment_not_recognised, declined_cash_withdrawal, exchange_rate, exchange_via_app, failed_transfer, get_disposable_virtual_card, get_physical_card, passcode_forgotten, pending_top_up, pending_transfer, receiving_money, reverted_card_payment?, top_up_by_cash_or_cheque, top_up_reverted, topping_up_by_card, transfer_fee_charged, transfer_into_account, transfer_timing, verify_my_identity, verify_source_of_funds.\n\nImportant domain-specific distinctions:\n\n**Transaction Type Definitions:**\n- \"cancel_transfer\" refers to requests to actively cancel, revert, or undo a TRANSFER transaction (moving money between accounts) that the user initiated\n- \"beneficiary_not_allowed\" refers to transfers that were STOPPED, BLOCKED, or REJECTED by the system (not by user request) - typically due to recipient/beneficiary restrictions or compliance issues\n- \"failed_transfer\" refers to transfers that failed to complete due to technical or processing errors\n- \"top_up_reverted\" refers specifically to reversals of TOP-UP transactions (adding money to an account from external sources)\n- \"reverted_card_payment?\" refers to card payment reversals, which is different from both transfers and top-ups\n\n**Key Classification Rules:**\n\n1. **Stopped/Blocked Transfers:** If a user asks WHY a transfer was stopped, blocked, rejected, or didn't go through (implying the system prevented it), classify as \"beneficiary_not_allowed\" - NOT \"cancel_transfer\". The user is asking about a system-imposed restriction, not requesting a cancellation.\n\n2. **User-Initiated Cancellations:** If a user is actively requesting to cancel, stop, or revert a transfer they initiated, classify as \"cancel_transfer\".\n\n3. **Transaction Type Identification:** Pay attention to the specific type of transaction mentioned:\n   - Transfer = moving money between accounts → use transfer-related categories\n   - Top-up = adding money to account from external source → use top_up_reverted for reversals\n   - Card payment = purchases with card → use reverted_card_payment?\n\n4. **Ambiguous Terms:** When users use generic terms like \"transaction\" or \"payment\" without specifying type:\n   - Look for context clues (mentions of recipients, beneficiaries, sending money → likely transfer)\n   - Questions about why something was stopped/blocked → likely \"beneficiary_not_allowed\"\n   - Requests to cancel/revert → likely \"cancel_transfer\"\n\n5. **Question Intent:** Distinguish between:\n   - \"Why was X stopped/blocked/rejected?\" → Asking about system restriction → \"beneficiary_not_allowed\"\n   - \"Can I cancel/stop X?\" or \"I want to cancel X\" → Requesting action → \"cancel_transfer\"\n   - \"X failed\" or \"X didn't work\" → Technical failure → \"failed_transfer\"\n\n6. **PIN/Passcode Questions:**\n   - Questions about accessing, receiving, or getting a PIN number (especially for new cards) → \"get_physical_card\"\n   - Questions about forgotten or lost passcodes/PINs → \"passcode_forgotten\"\n   - Key distinction: Getting access to a NEW PIN is part of the physical card setup process, not a forgotten passcode issue\n\n7. **Top-up Status Questions:**\n   - \"Top-up not showing\" or \"where is my top-up\" without mentioning reversal → \"pending_top_up\"\n   - \"Top-up showing AND asking about reversal\" or \"money reversed\" → \"top_up_reverted\"\n   - Key distinction: When a user explicitly mentions or asks about money being REVERSED in the context of a top-up, this indicates concern about a reversal, not just a pending status\n   - If the query includes both visibility issues AND reversal concerns, prioritize \"top_up_reverted\" as it addresses the more specific concern about money going back\n\n**Analysis Strategy:**\n- Read the entire query carefully\n- Identify the transaction type (transfer, top-up, card payment, card setup, etc.)\n- Identify the user's intent (asking why something happened, requesting an action, reporting a problem)\n- Look for specific keywords that indicate reversals, blocks, failures, or cancellations\n- Match the combination of transaction type and intent to the appropriate category"
 },
